{
  "text": "Diabetic patients have an increased propensity for cerebrovascular accidents, in part attributed to: a high level of platelet dysfunction, progressive atherosclerosis arising from an altered lipid profile, insulin resistance, hypertension, microalbuminuria, obesity, carotid intima-media thickness, and endothelial dysfunction [CITATION_1] . The benefit of existing therapeutic strategies in lowering incidence of stroke is quite evident. Anti-hypertensive drugs such as angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, hypolipidemic drugs (statins) and anti-platelet drugs (aspirin and clopidogrel) are known to be therapeutically beneficial in the treatment of cardiovascular disease in diabetics (International Diabetes Federation 2005) . A meta-regression analysis of controlled trials of stroke has shown that aspirin-based antiplatelet therapy evinces a significant efficacy in stroke patients [CITATION_2] . Moreover, such efficacy has been recapitulated in ischemic stroke among diabetic subjects [CITATION_3] . Systematic assessment of data from clinical studies have shown that anti-hypertensive drugs (diuretics or angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors) and hypolipidemic drugs (simvastatin) reduces the recurrence of stroke [CITATION_4] . These secondary prevention strategies have also been noted to be useful in treating ischemic stroke patients suffering from diabetics [CITATION_5] . These pharmacotherapeutic strategies display a favourable effect with regard to primary outcome parameters in stroke patients [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] ONTARGET Investigators et al. 2008) . Although these currently approved treatment strategies have proven useful in improving outcomes [CITATION_8] , diabetic patients continue to have a higher risk of adverse cerebrovascular events compared with that in nondiabetic patients [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
  "correct_citation": {
